# Database Schema Rules

## Schema Organization

- Schema is split into domain-scoped files in `packages/database/prisma/schema/`
- File naming: `NN_domain.prisma` (numbered prefix for load order)
- `00_datasource.prisma` must always contain generator + datasource
- Each file has a header comment with domain name and owning service
- When adding a new domain, create a new numbered file — NEVER append to existing domain files

## Table Design for Scale

- All tables MUST have `id` (UUID), `createdAt`, `updatedAt`
- Clinical data MUST have `deletedAt` for soft delete — never hard delete
- Multi-tenant tables MUST have `organizationId` with `@@index`
- Add `@@index` for EVERY field used in WHERE, ORDER BY, or JOIN
- Use `@@unique` constraints for business uniqueness (e.g., `[mrn, organizationId]`)
- JSONB fields (`Json` type) for flexible metadata — but don't over-use for queryable data
- Mark PHI/PII fields with `// PHI` comment

## Naming

- Table names: `@@map("snake_case_plural")` (e.g., `@@map("patients")`)
- Column names: `@map("snake_case")` (e.g., `@map("created_at")`)
- Model names: PascalCase (e.g., `Patient`, `CaseStudyLink`)
- Foreign keys: `<entity>Id` in Prisma, `<entity>_id` in database

## Relationships

- Always define both sides of a relation
- Use explicit relation names for ambiguous relations (e.g., `@relation("CaseCreator")`)
- Self-referential: use named relation (e.g., `@relation("PatientMerge")`)
- Many-to-many: use explicit join table (e.g., `UserRole`), not Prisma implicit

## Migration Safety

- Never rename columns in production — add new column, migrate data, drop old
- Never drop tables with data — add `deletedAt` flag instead
- Test migrations on a copy of production data before deploying
- Migration files are immutable once pushed — create new migration for changes
